The more transverse the tubes of are, the less transverse equidistribution holds, but the more shortening occurs. The less transverse, the more transverse equidistribution holds, but the less shortening occurs. Hopefully we can make some tradeoff between shortening and equidistribution to obtain an efficient bound.

It is likely true that we do not want to reduce to analysis on some translation of , since the exponents in refined decoupling are better the higher the dimension we are working in. So perhaps there is a different way to exploit equidistribution without having to work in the lower dimensional variety.
